Proxy : is a structural design patterns which controls access to an original object for purposes like lazy loading or caching.
     - Control access, lazy init, caching, or protect the real object
     - Proxy manages the service object's lifecycle
     - Single proxy wrapping one service


*** Spring and Spring Boot heavily rely on the Proxy pattern through dynamic proxies (JDK or CGLIB) for AOP, transaction management, and scoped beans, controlling access and adding behaviors to objects at runtime.
***
Proxy Implementation
Proxy provides lazy loading for a heavy image object, loading only when displayed.

Step 1: Define the subject interface.
public interface Image {
    void display();
}

Step 2: Real subject (heavy operation).
public class RealImage implements Image {
    private String filename;
    public RealImage(String filename) {
        this.filename = filename;
        loadFromDisk();
    }
    private void loadFromDisk() {
        System.out.println("Loading " + filename);
    }
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Displaying " + filename);
    }
}

Step 3: Proxy (controls access).
public class ProxyImage implements Image {
    private RealImage realImage;
    private String filename;
    public ProxyImage(String filename) { this.filename = filename; }
    public void display() {
        if (realImage == null) {
            realImage = new RealImage(filename);  // Lazy init
        }
        realImage.display();
    }
}

Step 4: Client usage.
public class ProxyDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Image image = new ProxyImage("test.jpg");
        image.display();  // Loads: Loading test.jpg \n Displaying test.jpg
        image.display();  // Cached: Displaying test.jpg
    }
}

*** Proxy delays expensive operations until needed, managing the real object's creation.


